com.datamirror.ts.target.publication.userexit.kafka

Interface KafkaCustomOperationProcessorIF

  • All Known Implementing Classes:
    com.datamirror.ts.target.publication.userexit.sample.kafka.AbstractAvroKcop, com.datamirror.ts.target.publication.userexit.sample.kafka.AbstractKcop, com.datamirror.ts.target.publication.userexit.sample.kafka.AbstractNonAvroKcop, KcopDefaultBehaviorIntegrated, KcopJsonFormatIntegrated, KcopJsonSingleRowAuditFormatIntegrated, KcopLiveAuditSingleRowIntegrated, KcopMultiRowAvroLiveAuditIntegrated, KcopSingleRowAvroAuditHeadersIntegrated, KcopSingleRowAvroAuditIntegrated, KcopTopicMappingIntegrated

    public interface KafkaCustomOperationProcessorIF

    This interface enables a user to determine the Kafka ProducerRecords to be written to the Kafka cluster in response to events which occur on the IIDR (CDC) source.

    PROGRAM FLOW:

    INIT:
    Implementations of the Kafka Custom Operation Processor (KCOP) subscribe to events for which they wish to have Kafak Records written for in the initialization method. Other actions are also possible such as logging event messages, etc.

    Create Producer Records:
    Each source operation event which is subscribed to will result in a call to the createProducerRecords method. Events which are not subscribed to will result in no call being made to this method and, consequently, no Kafka producer records being written to user data topics in kafka as a result of these events.
    Multiple threads are employed to process source database events in parallel and so the calls to this method will be potentially made from multiple threads. It may be the case that operations are not processed in the order the occurred on the source database, however if the Kafka Producer Records resulting from the createProducerRecords call refer to the same Kafka topic and partition, they will be ultimately written to that Kafka topic in the order the source events occurred on the source database. ie. Although potentially formatted out of order, the write order to the actual Kafka topic and partition will be done in order for this replication session.

    Finish:
    IN response to a normal shutdown, the Finish() method will be called. There will be no further calls to the createProducerRecords method for this replication session. It is not mandated that anything specific be done in this method, it is a convenience for the implementor of the KCOP.

    KafkaCustomOperationProcessorIF Specifics:

    This interface currently supports subscription to the following events:
    ReplicationEventTypes.BEFORE_INSERT_EVENT,
    ReplicationEventTypes.BEFORE_DELETE_EVENT,
    ReplicationEventTypes.BEFORE_UPDATE_EVENT

    TIPS:
    1) Kafka Operations are not necessarily processed in the order operations occurred in the original source log stream.
    2) Kafka operations may be processed in parallel and attention must be paid to non-thread safe objects.
    3) Kafka Operations are "Before" operations vs. "After" in terms of the old user exit convention.
    4) the processing of an operation may return from 0 to n output operations to be applied.
    5) Only add new ProduceRecords to the return value of the ProducerRecord ArrayList.
    6) If a KCOP requires external libraries, ensure these do not conflict with the ones loaded by the CDC Kafka Target. Validate against the install ../lib directory.

      • createProducerRecords

        java.util.ArrayList<org.apache.kafka.clients.producer.ProducerRecord<byte[],byte[]>> createProducerRecords(KafkaKcopOperationInIF kafkaKcopOperationIn,
                                                                                                           KafkaKcopReplicationCoordinatorIF kafkaKcopCoordinator)
                                                                                                    throws com.datamirror.ts.target.publication.userexit.UserExitException
        This method returns zero or more new Kafka ProducerRecord 's in response to an event on the source database described by the kafkaKcopOperationIn parameter.

        This method can be called by multiple threads concurrently and thus events are potentially processed in a differing order than they occurred on the source database. Ultimately the records resulting from calls to this method will be written to the Kafka cluster in order at a topic/partition granularity for the replication session. This is guaranteed regardless of which thread processes a given source replication event.

        It is required for the user to ensure they create a new ProducerRecord for each added to the list. To attempt to reuse an old ProducerRecord might result in the values of previously processed/formatted changing and thus being incorrect. See the Sample KCOPs for an example.

        Care must be taken with Non-thread safe objects. The KCOP KcoppDefaultBehaviorSample shows how to have each thread create its own non-threadsafe objects and store their specific instances of them with the setKcopThreadSpecificContext() method available from the passed in KafkaKcopReplicationCoordinatorIF.

        It is acceptable for the returned ArrayList to be null, which indicates no ProducerRecords are to be written to Kafka on behalf of this replication event.

        Kafka Producer records returned in the ArrayList which refer to the same Kafka topic/partition are written in list order to the Kafka topic.
        Parameters:
        kafkaKcopOperationIn - - Contains information relevant to the current event/operation being processed.
        kafkaKcopCoordinator - - Contains subscription scope information including functionality for storage of each thread's non-threadsafe objects.
        Returns:
        - A list of Kafka ProducerRecords to be written to the Kafka cluster.
        Throws:
        com.datamirror.ts.target.publication.userexit.UserExitException - can be thrown

      • createKafkaRecords

        default java.util.ArrayList<com.datamirror.ts.target.publication.userexit.KafkaRecord<byte[],byte[]>> createKafkaRecords(KafkaKcopOperationInIF kafkaKcopOperationIn,
                                                                                                                         KafkaKcopReplicationCoordinatorIF kafkaKcopCoordinator)
                                                                                                                  throws com.datamirror.ts.target.publication.userexit.UserExitException
        This method returns zero or more new Kafka records in response to an event on the source database described by the kafkaKcopOperationIn parameter.

        By default the method calls createProducerRecords and then converts the resulting ProducerRecord 's to Kafka records. Subclasses are encouraged to override this method and provide a more efficient implementation.

        The method is called instead of createProducerRecords when a custom classpath is defined for KCOP execution.
        Parameters:
        kafkaKcopOperationIn - - Contains information relevant to the current event/operation being processed.
        kafkaKcopCoordinator - - Contains subscription scope information including functionality for storage of each thread's non-threadsafe objects.
        Returns:
        - A list of Kafka records to be written to the Kafka cluster.
        Throws:
        com.datamirror.ts.target.publication.userexit.UserExitException - can be thrown

     throws com.datamirror.ts.target.publication.userexit.UserExitException
        This method will be called during shutdown. It will only be called once the last encodeAvroRecord method call has been made and resultant records are confirmed to have been written to Kafka. After being called, no further calls to encodeAvroRecord will be made for this session of replication. Finish will be called once for the user exit.
